 to be a Russian base. The Russians in turn also concentrated there, in order to build a base, sending repeated expeditions along the river. Both China, who claimed to rule along the Amur, and Japan, only just `opened up' by Commodore Perry's expedition, were involved - indeed, the British used a Japanese port as their advanced base. The United States had only recently reached the Pacific coast and several Americans had their eyes on Russian Alaska and Hawaii as territories for future acquisitions. All this meant the Allies hadto tread very delicately in Pacific waters. The war in Europe ended before a decisive action could take place in the Pacific. Ironically, having lost in the fighting, the Russians ended with a great advance in their territory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCrimean War, 1853-1856xCampaigns. 0aCrimean War, 1853-1856xNaval operations, British. 0aCrimean War, 1853-1856xNaval operations. 4aMilitary History. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Military / General.2bisacsh  aAmur River.  aChina.  aCrimean War.  aInternational conflict.  aJapan.  aNaval campaign.  aPacific Ocean.  aPetropavlovsk battle.  aRussian territories.  aUnited States.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615638040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846156380423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846156380/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles